# Introduction

Epidemiological delay distributions are subject to double interval censoring: both the primary event (e.g. infection) and the secondary event (e.g. symptom onset) are observed within discrete time windows rather than at exact times [@placeholder_charniga; @placeholder_park].
If ignored, this censoring biases parameter estimates.
Right truncation introduces further bias because recent observations are systematically missing due to reporting delays.

`estimate_dist()` fits delay distributions from linelist data while accounting for both of these biases.
The censoring windows need not be daily; the date-based interface supports arbitrary window widths.
The function uses a Stan model that vendors likelihood functions from the [primarycensored](https://primarycensored.epinowcast.org/) package.
If you use `estimate_dist()`, please cite `primarycensored` in addition to `EpiNow2`.

The result is an `<estimate_dist>` object (inheriting from `<epinowfit>`) that gives access to the Stan fit for diagnostics.
Use `get_parameters()` to extract the fitted `<dist_spec>`, ready for use in other _EpiNow2_ functions such as `estimate_infections()`.
Common use cases include estimating the incubation period (infection to symptom onset), the reporting delay (symptom onset to case report), or the serial interval (symptom onset in infector-infectee pairs).
Generation time estimation (infection to infection) typically requires known infection times for both infector and infectee, which calls for more complex models such as those in [epidist](https://epidist.epinowcast.org/).

For more flexible delay distribution modelling, `epidist` supports latent variable models and regression on covariates.
`primarycensored` operates at a lower level, working directly with numeric delays and censoring windows.
Both packages can be used independently of `EpiNow2`.

# Set up

```{r setup}
library(EpiNow2) # nolint: unused_import_linter.
library(primarycensored)
options(mc.cores = 2)
```

# Simulating censored delay data

We simulate 200 individual delay observations from a lognormal distribution with known parameters.
Each call to `rprimarycensored()` returns a single censored delay, so `n = 200` produces 200 observations.

Primary event dates are drawn uniformly over a two-week period.
For each observation, `rprimarycensored()` applies daily censoring (both primary and secondary windows of width 1) and right truncation at `D` days.
We set a per-observation truncation time `D = 30`, representing the time between the primary event and the date of data extraction.

```{r simulate}
set.seed(42)
n <- 200
D <- 30

true_meanlog <- 1.5
true_sdlog <- 0.75

pdate_lwr <- as.Date("2023-01-01") +
  sample(0:13, n, replace = TRUE)

delays <- rprimarycensored(
  n = n,
  rdist = rlnorm,
  meanlog = true_meanlog,
  sdlog = true_sdlog,
  pwindow = 1,
  D = D
)

linelist <- data.frame(
  pdate_lwr = pdate_lwr,
  sdate_lwr = pdate_lwr + delays,
  obs_date = pdate_lwr + D
)

head(linelist)
```

```{r hist, fig.width = 6, fig.height = 4}
hist(
  delays, breaks = 20,
  main = "Simulated censored delays",
  xlab = "Delay (days)", col = "steelblue", border = "white"
)
```

The data frame has three columns:

- `pdate_lwr`: lower bound of the primary event date (e.g. date of infection).
- `sdate_lwr`: lower bound of the secondary event date (e.g. date of symptom onset).
- `obs_date`: the date at which the data were extracted, determining the right truncation point for each observation.

Upper bounds for the primary and secondary event windows default to one day after the lower bounds (daily censoring).

If you have numeric delays without dates, you can construct a date-based data frame using a dummy origin date (e.g. `pdate_lwr = as.Date("2020-01-01")`) and adding delays to derive `sdate_lwr` and `obs_date`.

# Fitting the model

We pass the linelist directly to `estimate_dist()`.
Internally the function converts dates to numeric intervals, aggregates identical delay-censoring combinations, and fits the model via MCMC.

```{r fit}
result <- estimate_dist(
  linelist,
  dist = "lognormal"
)
params <- get_parameters(result)
params$delay
```

The `result` object also provides access to the Stan fit via `result$fit`, which can be used for convergence diagnostics.

# Checking parameter recovery

The printed output above shows the posterior summary for each parameter.
The posterior credible intervals should overlap with the true values used in the simulation (`meanlog = 1.5`, `sdlog = 0.75`).
